04316nam a2200541Ia 9781927356067DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a9781927356067  a(DE-B1597)665348  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV109.P734bS77 2013eb 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a361.6/109712090432231 aStrikwerda, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Wages of Relief :bCities and the Unemployed in Prairie Canada, 1929–39 /cEric Strikwerda. 1aEdmonton, Alberta : bAthabasca University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (333 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWorking Canadians: Books from the CCLH00tFrontmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early part of the Dirty Thirties, the Canadian prairie city was a relatively safe haven. Having faced recession before the Great War and then again in the early 1920s, municipalities already had relief apparatuses in place to deal with poverty and unemployment. Until 1933, responsibilty for the care of the urban poor remained with local governments, but when the farms failed that year, and the Depression deepened, western Canadian cities suffered tremendously. Recognizing the severity of the crisis, the national government intervened. Evolving federal programs and policies took over responsibility for the delivery of relief to the single unemployed, while the government simultaneously withdrew financing for all public works projects. Setting municipal relief administrations of the 1930s within a wider literature on welfare and urban poor relief, Strikwerda highlights the legacy on which relief policymakers relied in determining policy directions, as well as the experiences of the individuals and families who depended on relief for their survival. Focusing on three prairie cities—Edmonton, Saskatoon, and Winnipeg—Strikwerda argues that municipal officials used their power to set policy to address what they perceived to be the most serious threats to the social order stemming from the economic crisis. By analyzing the differing ways in which local relief programs treated married and single men, he also explores important gendered dynamics at work in the response of city administrators to the social and economic upheaval of the Depression. Probing the mindset of local elites struggling in extraordinary circumstances, The Wages of Relief describes the enduring impact of the policy changes made in the 1930s in the direction of a broad, national approach to unemployment—an approach that ushered in Canada’s modern welfare system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCities and townsxSocial aspectszPrairie ProvincesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMunicipal governmentzPrairie ProvincesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic welfare administrationzPrairie ProvincesxHistoryy20th century. 0aUnemployedxGovernment policyzPrairie ProvincesxHistoryy20th century. 0aUrban economicsxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781927356067423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781927356067/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles